\begin_layout Section*
Excerise 26
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\series medium
The Proposed modification is to bet 6 times after losing a bet twice; otherwise,
 successive bets in the event of a previous winning bet should follow the
 same logic as the original St.
 Petersburg system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The logic 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P(LLL)=\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{3}=\frac{8}{27}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P(W|LL)=\frac{P(WLL)}{P(LL)}=\frac{\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{2}*\frac{1}{3}}{\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{2}}=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $E(LLW)=-1*\frac{2}{3}-1*\frac{2}{3}+6*\frac{1}{3}=2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basically the idea is that the chances of a losing steak dimishes over the
 long run; thus, at the point of losing steak, betting more may cause the
 Expected gain to level out as the probabily of a continued L over L dimishes
 over time.
 The idea being while 
\begin_inset Formula $P(L|LL)=\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

, the event that n loses in a row occurs will significantly lessen.
 The up side being, if the guy has a bad losing streak, the game ends faster.
\end_layout

